PARAGRAPH.#text: By Christopher Hinton NEW YORK (Dow Jones) -- Boeing Co.'s commercial aircraft facilities were quiet Monday after the manufacturer's 27,000 machinists walked off production lines in protest of a proposed labor contract they said fell short on healthcare benefits and job security. "We will continue this fight 'one day longer' than the company can afford until they meet our demands," the International Machinists and Aerospace Workers told its members late Sunday on its Web site. Tom Buffenbarger, the union's national leader, said in the Seattle Times that if the strike does cost Boeing $100 million a day in lost sales, as many Wall Street analysts predict, it will take strikers one month and a week to drain the company's $10 billion cash balance.

NEW YORK (CBS.MW) --Investors played it close to the vest Monday, a day ahead of
    an important meeting of the Federal Reserve's policy-making panel. According to
    preliminary figures, the Dow
    Jones Industrial Average

declined 59.85 points, or 0.5 percent, to 10,853.47. The
    index had fallen as much as 167.52 points in the morning. Trading activity slowed to a
    crawl. "I haven't seen it this quiet in six months to a year," said

, president of Herzog Heine Geduld. "The volume is telling you they're
    not sure which way [the Federal Reserve meeting] will go."The Nasdaq
    Composite

advanced 33.72 points, or 1.3 percent, to 2,561.58. The Standard
    & Poor's 500 Index
rose 0.1 percent.
